    {
      "label": "find_prime_p",
      "instructions": "Find the smallest prime $p$ such that there exists an integer $n$ satisfying $n^4 \equiv -1 \pmod{p^2}$. Note: For $n^4 \equiv -1 \pmod{p}$ to have a solution, $p$ must be of the form $8k+1$ (since $n^8 \equiv 1 \pmod{p}$ and $n^4 \not\equiv 1$). Check primes $p \equiv 1 \pmod{8}$ sequentially. For each $p$, check if $n^4 \equiv -1 \pmod{p}$ has a solution, and if so, check if any such solution $n$ can be lifted to $n^4 \equiv -1 \pmod{p^2}$ using Hensel's Lemma (which requires $f'(n) \not\equiv 0 \pmod{p}$)."
    },
    {
      "label": "find_least_m",
      "instructions": "Once the smallest prime $p$ is identified, find all solutions to $x^4 + 1 \equiv 0 \pmod{p^2}$ in the range $0 \le x < p^2$. Identify the smallest such positive integer $m$."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the results from the two helpers. The first helper provides the prime $p$. The second helper provides the smallest root $m$ modulo $p^2$. The final answer should be presented as the pair (p, m) or as requested by the specific format (though the prompt asks for 'least prime p... then find least m', implying a sequence or a specific value; I will provide the values for p and m clearly)."
}
